 ðŸ. ðð«ðžðšð¤ ð’ð­ðšð­ðžð¦ðžð§ð­ :::---
      >> The break statement is used to terminate the loop immediately.
      >> The program resumes control at the next statement in the code.

   For Example ;;;
      class Main
      {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            if (i == 5) {
                break; // Exit the loop when i equals 5
            }
            System.out.println("Value of i: " + i);
        }                                //1 2 3 4

-------------------><----------------><------------------

 ðŸ. ð‚ð¨ð§ð­ð¢ð§ð®ðž ð’ð­ðšð­ðžð¦ðžð§ð­  :::---
     >> The continue statement is used to skip the current iteration of the loop it continue with next.
     >> It doesn't terminate the loop but forces the next iteration to begin immediately.

   For Example ;;;
     class Main {
      public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0) {
                continue; // Skip even numbers
            }
            System.out.println("Value of i: " + i);
        }                              //1 3 5 7 9


